124 /* Table and tablespace flags are generally not used for the Antelope file
125 format except for the low order bit, which is used differently depending on
126 where the flags are stored.
127
128 ==================== Low order flags bit =========================
129 | REDUNDANT | COMPACT | COMPRESSED and DYNAMIC
130 SYS_TABLES.TYPE | 1 | 1 | 1
131 dict_table_t::flags | 0 | 1 | 1
132 FSP_SPACE_FLAGS | 0 | 0 | 1
133 fil_space_t::flags | 0 | 0 | 1
134
135 Before the 5.1 plugin, SYS_TABLES.TYPE was always DICT_TABLE_ORDINARY (1)
136 and the tablespace flags field was always 0. In the 5.1 plugin, these fields
137 were repurposed to identify compressed and dynamic row formats.
138
139 The following types and constants describe the flags found in dict_table_t
140 and SYS_TABLES.TYPE. Similar flags found in fil_space_t and FSP_SPACE_FLAGS
141 are described in fsp0fsp.h. */

903 /** PADDING HEURISTIC BASED ON LINEAR INCREASE OF PADDING TO AVOID
904 COMPRESSION FAILURES
905 (Note: this is relevant only for compressed indexes)
906 GOAL: Avoid compression failures by maintaining information about the
907 compressibility of data. If data is not very compressible then leave
908 some extra space 'padding' in the uncompressed page making it more
909 likely that compression of less than fully packed uncompressed page will
910 succeed.
911
912 This padding heuristic works by increasing the pad linearly until the
913 desired failure rate is reached. A "round" is a fixed number of
914 compression operations.
915 After each round, the compression failure rate for that round is
916 computed. If the failure rate is too high, then padding is incremented
917 by a fixed value, otherwise it's left intact.
918 If the compression failure is lower than the desired rate for a fixed
919 number of consecutive rounds, then the padding is decreased by a fixed
920 value. This is done to prevent overshooting the padding value,
921 and to accommodate the possible change in data compressibility. */
922

928
929 /** Amount by which padding is increased. */

931
932 /** Percentage of compression failures that are allowed in a single
933 round */
934 extern ulong zip_failure_threshold_pct;
935
936 /** Maximum percentage of a page that can be allowed as a pad to avoid
937 compression failures */
938 extern ulong zip_pad_max;
